Israeli children returned to school after the Gaza war
Thousands of Israeli children in the territories near the Gaza Strip returned to school on Monday after spending summer in bomb shelters, when rockets and mines rained on their settlements during the 50-day war between Israel and Hamas, while schools in the Gaza Strip remained closed as the territory recovered from the fighting.
The start of school was a source of joy and excitement for missile-affected settlements in southern Israel, but the signs of fighting remained fresh.
In the southern town of Ashdod, Pashosh kindergarten, which had been hit by a rocket, removed fragments from the walls and roller coasts before the students arrived.
"We're a little scared, but we're looking forward to the future," said Ronite Bart, a resident of Kibbutza Saad and an English teacher at his school.
