Genetic disorder is often misdiagnosed
Brittany reported that she had spent many years thinking she was gonna die after an incorrect diagnosis.
Karin Rogers spent most of her teenage years thinking she had only a few years to live after she was diagnosed with another disease.
In fact, she had Charco-Marie-Touta (SMT) disease, a group of genetic disorders that caused nerve damage outside her brain and spine.
The charity CMT UK reported that the wrong diagnosis was a common problem among people with SMT because so little was known about this condition.
Some 23,000 people in Britain are believed to have SMTs that can cause motor symptoms, such as muscle weakness, insecure walking, and flexed toes.
The sick may feel numbness or pain, and the condition does not heal and progress, which means that the symptoms increase over time.
When Rogers was 13, she thought she was suffering from Friedrich's attack, a condition that was very bad.
Rogers thought she'd be chained to a wheelchair by the time she was 18 and die before she turned 30.
The mother of two children, now 51, said, "I knew as a child that I couldn't do what the others could.
I fell every day, and it took me more time.
I've never been on roller skates or skateboard with other kids, and I've been bullied a lot at school because I've been walking and running.
Rogers said that when she was 13, after several surgeries to release the achille tendon and straighten her feet, she looked into the medical records when her doctor left the room and it said she had an AF.
"I felt guilty because I snuck my nose where I shouldn't, so I didn't tell anyone, but I came home, found information about it in the library, and wrote to the AF Association," she said.
When I received the information in return, I was shocked and experienced the worst panic possible.
