The deputies proposed to expedite the entry into force of the Personal Data Act
If the initiative succeeds, these Russians will not be stored on servers abroad as of 1 January 2015
A draft law has been submitted to the State for the extension of the date of entry into force of the already adopted Russian Personal Data Act from 1 September 2016 to 1 January 2015.
The initiative is part of the legislative framework of the lower house.
It was sponsored by the deputies of the State Duma, Vadim Dengin, Jaroslav Nelov (LDPR), Evgeny Fedorov (the only Russia), Vladimir Parahin (the just Russia) and Alexander Yushchenko (KPRF).
Such a change, in the view of the authors of the initiative, would help to ensure the rights of citizens of the Russian Federation to preserve personal data and to respect the confidentiality of communications in information and telecommunications networks more quickly and effectively.
The Act, the entry into force of which is a matter for parliamentarians, requires that Russians ' personal data be kept on the territory of the Russian Federation and processed on the Internet.
It also makes it mandatory to record, systematize, accumulate, store, clarify and extract personal data from citizens of the Russian Federation in databases located on Russian territory, as well as to indicate the location of such databases.
In addition, the law gives Roscomnadzor the right, on the basis of a court decision, to restrict access to information processed in violation of Russian legislation in the field of personal data.
The Act also proposes the creation of so-called "blacklists" of offending sites, an automated information system called "Risk of violators of the rights of personal data subjects".
This law was passed by the State Duma in the summer.
The draft law was sponsored by Andrei Lugova and Vadim Dengin of LDPR and Alexander Yushchenko of CLCF.
Dengin and Yushchenko are also among the sponsors of the current bill to postpone the date of entry into force of the already adopted law.
Those who don't have data centres in the Russian Federation will have to pay rent.
Commenting on the bill submitted to the State today, Leonid Levin, the first deputy head of the Duma Committee on Information Policy, stated that he saw no problem in postponing the date of entry into force of the Personal Data Protection Act.
According to him, those companies that would not have their own Russian personal data stores on Russian territory by 1 January 2015 would be able to rent them, for example, "Rostelcoma," which repeatedly said that they were willing to rent their servers and already provided their servers, from Mail Group, Western companies that are now providing their servers."
"There are also several independent data centres ready to cooperate in this area," he added.
"If companies decide to comply with the law and continue working on the territory of the Russian Federation, I see no problem - they will have technological accommodation opportunities", Levin summarized.
Dispute Bill
Immediately after the publication of the draft law, the Russian Electronic Communications Association expressed concern that many global Internet services would no longer be available to Russians if the bill were adopted.
These include online booking services for airline tickets and hotels.
In the view of the association, "the draft law deprives subjects of personal data - citizens of the Russian Federation of the right to dispose of their own data by making it mandatory that their recording, systematization, etc. should be ensured only in databases located on the territory of the Russian Federation".
RAEC ' s statement emphasizes that a more effective measure would be to create a mechanism to inform the user of the location of the recording, systematizing its personal data.
In such a case, it will be possible to choose the territory in which the actions will be carried out.
The adoption of similar personal data "localization" bills in other countries has led to the abandonment of global services and significant economic losses.
