The more physical damage one person can cause to another, the more he can dictate his conditions, and he communicates it with anger.
Researchers have also found evidence of their own hypotheses: physically strong people are more likely to be angry and to resort to manual use, feel free to impose conditions upon others that do not benefit them, and prefer to use force to resolve conflicts peacefully.
In response to the fact that anger is primarily an "emotion of bargaining", scientists have decided that the movements of each of the seven groups of muscles that create the angry expression of a face should present the angry individual with a stronger and more dangerous face - and thus force him to accept its terms as soon as possible in order to avoid conflict.
To test this hypothesis, researchers modelled on the computer the faces of each of the seven elements of the angry face and showed them to the informants.
Although the missed eyebrows or the chin that was moved forward did not individually make the face angry, the person with such features was recognized by a unanimous physical participant as stronger.
The anger of man, like that of animals, poses a threat: an exaggerated act of self - control that compels consent and submission.
A man blows his nostrils and presses his lips for the same purpose as a frog who blows up, or a grandmother who shows his fangs.
"The anger is `started' by the defendant's refusal to accept the situation, and the person immediately takes a form that shows the opposite side as effectively as possible of the consequences of the refusal.
But the most striking thing is that none of the components of the angry face is arbitrary, all of them expressing the same thing," noted Anthropologist John Tubi.
The Ministry of Communications has proposed 250 million rubles of the Crimea television and radio company.
The Ministry of Communications proposed to allocate 250 million rubles from the federal budget in 2014 to the autonomous non-profit organization The Crimea Teleradio.
This is referred to in the draft government decree prepared by the agency, which was reviewed by Lent.ru.
According to the explanatory note to the project, grants from the federal budget will be allocated "to cover the costs of creating conditions for extensive information coverage of the socio-economic situation and the development of the modern information space in the territory of the Republic of Crimea, including the acquisition of equipment".
In particular, it is intended to convert the hardware and studio unit, the video walls, the central hardware and the video server with the money allocated.
The acquisition of a mobile television station and a satellite transmitter is also planned.
In addition, the company will pay for the use of the fibre-optic line (WALS) and the repair of the energy system from the funds allocated.
Grants will be provided within the federal budget allocated to the Ministry of Communications.
The State Broadcasting Company Crimea was established in 1959 and broadcasts in seven languages: Ukrainian, Russian, Crimean Tatar, German, Greek, Bulgarian and Armenian.
To date, over 75 per cent of the peninsula has been reached by television broadcasting.
In 2011, Crime Television Company was licensed to broadcast digital television.
